{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17624719","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17624719"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T16:19:20+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T16:19:20+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16955"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16955","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16955"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0,0.9,0.1,0,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9645"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68684"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9645","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9645"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16955"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54142"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4926"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"9850"},{"type":"tags","id":"9854"},{"type":"tags","id":"10290"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22754"},{"type":"contributions","id":"22759"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68684","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/68684"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe atrioventricular node is a specialized region of cardiac conducting tissue located in the interatrial septum near the tricuspid valve.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the primary physiological function of the atrioventricular node?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Generates the heart\u0027s intrinsic rhythm","Delays electrical conduction between atria and ventricles","Coordinates contraction between left and right ventricles","Prevents retrograde conduction to the atria","Increases electrical signals from the atria"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe primary function of the atrioventricular node is to \u003Cstrong\u003Edelay electrical conduction between atria and ventricles\u003C/strong\u003E. This delay of approximately 120 milliseconds allows the atria to complete their contraction and empty blood into the ventricles before ventricular contraction begins.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGenerates the heart\u0027s intrinsic rhythm\u003C/strong\u003E - this is the function of the sinoatrial node, not the atrioventricular node\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECoordinates contraction between left and right ventricles\u003C/strong\u003E - this is primarily achieved by the bundle of His and Purkinje system\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPrevents retrograde conduction to the atria\u003C/strong\u003E - the atrioventricular node can conduct in both directions\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreases electrical signals from the atria\u003C/strong\u003E - the atrioventricular node actually decreases conduction velocity\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe slow conduction through the atrioventricular node is due to its unique cellular properties, including fewer gap junctions and different ion channel characteristics compared to other cardiac conducting tissue.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The atrioventricular node delays electrical conduction between atria and ventricles by approximately 120 milliseconds.","The atrioventricular node conducts action potentials at a slow velocity of 0.05 meters per second due to its unique ion channel properties.","The delay at the atrioventricular node allows atrial contraction to complete before ventricular contraction begins."],"references":["Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Edition: John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Limited; 2019"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54142"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16955"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54142","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/54142"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-10T10:10:00+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-10T10:10:35+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9645"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68684"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},